,Recommended,252630,11816746,"Posted: 22 August, 2014",all,NoSkillWill,"A mediocre title from a barren genre.So, graded on a curve, its great.Like many of these indie roguelikes, it lacks content something fierce. The main game is complete within the first 2 hours or so, sooner if you get a good early run and find the item that saves you from death... an infinite number of times. The enemies are surprisingly well designed, and some in dumb, crawley, flying, ranged and far-too-powerful-but-can-be-sneaked. The game isnt really scary but oh man, being chased by several flavors of indestructible horrors that chase you to the ends of the earth sure puts you on edge after a while.The enemies that can be killed can be looted for ammo or keys or money, but choosing not to loot them prevents them from respawning on the level and HOLY BALLS that is a fantastic idea! The mechanic allows a good risk-for-reward mentality to the later levels. The controls are nice and the physics feel good. There are a good range of spells to unlock and destructible terrain is always a pleasure to mess around with, though I never found a hidden room destroying walls even once so it feels like a missed opportinity unless I am incredibly dumb or unlucky to have not found one.It does have it's problems though, besides it's brevity I mean. The game's graphics are♥♥♥♥♥♥ This is not really a problem to me normally, but after having two friends catching me playing and asking when minecraft was updated to include lizard-people I had to concede that the game didn't even try to distinguish itself. The textures are legitimately indestinguishable from those in minecraft in some areas, which saddens me because drawing a good 25x25 pixel texture is not difficult. Only having two inventory slots is fine and prohibits hoarding of key items, but what I found myself doing at the end of the day is sticking with the gun and dagger for 99% of the game, dropping the dagger for some dynamite whenever I found some, throwing it against a wall, than backtracking for a few seconds to get my dagger back. This worked great for me, but really broke the flow of the experience for me. Powerful monsters can be avoided entirely through sneaking. The sneaking itself was implemented quite well, but if you find the ""sneak shoes"" it makes the game about as hard as Dora the Explorers Big Birthday Adventure. There are rocks and distraction powers in the game, but it's all rendered moot since you can just sprint past all threats, and any enemy with the slightest bit of perceptive ability can be knifed in the face twice and downed without alerting anyone else. Any level that doesnt include the indestructible shoggoth or weeping angel lizard statues can be sprinted through with no risk whatsoever. Maybe I'm just too good, who knows... but I felt unchallenged, so mlg pros stay away.Last point, you can purchase or steal from storekeepers, but as far as I could tell there was no risk involved in just knifing the shopkeep and taking his whole inventory. If you've ever played ""Spelunky"", the risk involved in agressing the storeowner was high and immediately obvious. There is no risk here.Overall, I'd have to say that it was fun knifing cthulu-spawn in the face as Disney's Kim Possible. Assuming this game will get further updates to counter it's short lifespan, it's worth a purchase."
