76561198011064182,Recommended,252630,8523789,"Posted: 2 January, 2014",all,AlphaRhoRho,"Aesthetically the game owes a lot to Minecraft, which is reasonable when you consider you can blow apart walls/floors or create new ones with spells.  It didn't add anything to the game, but it didn't detract as much as I was worried it might.  The enemy models were still entertaining (I loved the fish people and the cthonians).  The sound design was well done, keeping things extremely tense, but still being necessary to know when someone was walking up behind you.Gameplay-wise, it was somewhere in between true rogue-like and the kind of game I prefer where most of your advancement carries over between attempts.  Unlocked levels and artifacts carry over (or CAN carry over, in the case of artifacts, provided you found a chest to store them in before you die), though trying to jump into the later unlocked levels without the advancement from the earlier levels is foolish at best, so I found it better to just restart at the beginning anyway.One thing I found interesting was that the strategy that ended up working for me was finding a shop in the first area that had a health pack (the only way in the game to get ""continues"") and, instead of trying to save up your artifacts to purchase it (since you'll need them to buy continues) just save up bullets until you have a dozen or so and kill the shopkeeper.  Then you can loot the health pack, maybe a luck amulet, and a pair of boots which will keep you going for the rest of the game.The game isn't long, though I haven't played through the Mountains of Madness DLC.   There is a spell system in the game that I never even bothered with, since that spends artifacts and I was hoarding them for continues, though I do like that you get spells by praying to different elder gods.All in all it was an entertaining, tense, dungeon-crawly rogue-like with just a sprinkle of Lovecraft mythos on top.  No buyers remorse here."
