,Recommended,252630,14782569,"Posted: 7 March, 2015",all,RAIZO,"I love Eldritch but the funny thing about it is that I was at first disappointed (I initially thought there would be more backstory/adventuring involved, but I had little understanding of the type of game it was at the time, so that’s on me and in no way should it throw anyone off from enjoying it!).It’s only after putting 12+ hours into it that I now realize how great it is as far as rogue-likes are concerned.  Sure, there’s perma-death but you’ll keep the cash-monies you had in your bank chest upon resurrecting/exiting then restarting.  Also, if you’re new to this game the Mountains of Madness, Asylum and Halloween/Pumpkin additions were added after its release, for free!There’s a good bit of strategy involved if you wish to beat the 3 missions (MoM, Asylum and of course the library the game takes place in).  Pickaxes, dynamite and even a charm that gives the gun the ability to fire bullets that break the environment (all of which do it Minecraft-style) can be utilized to your advantage.  You can even pick up different kinds of packs,  like the med pack that can revive you upon death as long as you have 50 gem thingies (‘artifacts’ as the game puts it) to spend, and boots that can grant different abilities, like high jumping and speed.Be warned, though the enemies may look ‘cute-ish’, they can be, and often are, downright deadly!  And In keeping with the lore of Lovecraft and the retro/blocky graphics, the enemies look great in that classic, cheesy 50’s era way.On a final note, though Eldritch is certainly humorous at times, it’s still a horror game at its core and it certainly does justice to the godfather of modern sci-fi/horror, the man and legend that started it all, H.P. Lovecraft --- R.I.P. good sir, you live on through us all!!"
