76561198208426773,Recommended,252630,31809862,Posted: 17 May,all,jdacronym,"This is a game about flavor more than challenge. If you want something to play casually and have an affection for Lovecraft's fictional universe, you'll be amused.This blocky little first person roguelike pits your amnesiac librarian against multiple dungeons of plushie Lovecraftian monsters. This soft, cuddly presentation makes most of the monsters endearingly cute, and mostly robs them of their menace, which is beguiling until you get swarmed by them.It's not murderously difficult, a little stealth and platforming skill will get you away from most danger. A handful of unkillable monsters, including that was unfazed by basically all attacks, compensate for the general lack of monstery challenge and require you to not approach every situation identically. The achievement for finishing the game without taking damage seems like it'd be a challenge, though.Overall, the casual tone meant I was able to both access and enjoy the content the developers had put into the distinct dungeons, as well as come up with creative solutions. Once I scrounged enough TNT to dynamite my way to an exit (discovering hidden rooms with treasure and food in the process). In another, a magic block-making spell let me build a bridge over a hallway of monsters, Minecraft style. Having beaten it, I may not revisit it soon, but I definitely will for nostalgia's sake."
