,Recommended,252630,34867983,Posted: 10 September,all,Salty Juniper,"A Rogue-like loosely based on Lovecraft's mythos with a cute artstyle, Eldritch is a game that is both easy and unforgiving. This may sound like a contradiction, but the reason I describe it this way is that most enemies are real push-overs. Even without a weapon, you can easily beat most to death with decent maneuvering. The enemies are, however, dangerous, and if you aren't paying attention they can kill you in a few hits. When you die, you lose all of your weapons and items, as well as any currency you haven't stored in the bank. Each time you die, the areas are re-randomized (even the hub area), preventing players from brute-forcing the game through memorization.With fairly small areas to explore, combined with the ability to save and quit whenever and wherever you want, this is a great game for people with busy schedules, who want to play for only a few minutes.ProsCute artstyle.Minimalist, yet effective, sound design.A decent collection of weapons, powers, and items to choose from. You can only have one of each, though.Replayability due to the randomization.Satisfying combat.Great FOV range (60-120). This may sound like a minor detail, but I love playing at a high FOV.ConsIts regular $15 price is too high in my opinion.Although there is a diverse selection of enemies, they all fall into three simple categoriesWalk towards player and melee attackWalk towards player and shoot projectiles (either an orange or green ball)Fly towards player and shoot projectilesThe only change in this is one enemy, which is a living statue that can only attack when you look away. Sadly, this is the only interesting enemy design (in terms of gameplay).Difficulty is heavily reliant on RNG.You have to expect RNG to a certain extent with Rogue-likes, but it would've been nice to have a bit more balance. You can find overpowered items in easy areas, and underpowered items in hard areas. In other Rogue-likes, like Binding of Isaac, you don't really get overpowered until you've made a decent amount of progress.It's possible to enter areas that you can't exit, forcing you to respawn and lose all items. These areas seem somewhat intended, but they're still huge beginner's traps.From what I've seen so far, there's not much of an effort to mimic Lovecraft's works. The game does little to inspire the sense of dread that Lovecraft is famous for, and I haven't seen any attempt to replicate his writing style in the books that can be found throughout the game. As a fan of Lovecraft's stories myself, I feel I can safely say that this game is not necessarily a must-buy for Lovecraft fans.All things considered, I would highly recommend this game while it's on sale, but at full price I would encourage the consumer to put some thought into the purchase first.One thing to note: if you die at any point, you loseallprogress, except for areas you have already unlocked (with the exception of the last area). Not my cup of tea, but it doesn't detract from the quality of the game."
